Europe's Debt Write-Off Is Inevitable
Berkeley — — “That is just the Greek crisis”, “That is just the Greek and Irish crisis”, people once believed so, but now it's not allowed, because it is clearly a crisis of the euro zone.
Dealing with it is easier and more difficult than people usually think.
The economic logic of this crisis is quite simple.
Greece's financial problems exist.
Ireland's banking sector has problems.
Portugal's private debt market has problems.
Spain has problems in all three areas mentioned above.
Although the details differ, the conclusion is the same: all these countries must go through the painful process of reducing spending.
To offset the side effects of the tightening policy, the usual way is to combine domestic spending cuts and devaluation of the local currency.
The devaluation will enhance export competitiveness, which is to make up for domestic demand with foreign demand.
However, these countries are all eurozone countries. They do not have their own currency that can be devalued, so they can only use internal devaluation to replace external devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to increase export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding demand.
Actually, the determination of these crisis countries to tighten their belts is not small.
However, one economic variable has not changed with the adjustment of other variables, that is, the debt of the public and private sectors.
Government's accumulated debt has not changed in book value, and bank debt — — except for some debt owed to ordinary creditors (junior creditors) — has not changed much.
This simple fact puts the internal devaluation strategy in self-contradictory circumstances: the more salaries and other costs are reduced, the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending needs to be reduced and taxes increased in order to cope with government and its backers (such as banks) debt.
This, in turn, requires more internal devaluation, which further pushes up the debt burden, thus forming a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a recession.
Therefore, in order for the internal devaluation strategy to be effective, ways must be found to lower the debt value.
Government bonds must be restructured.
Bank debts must be converted to equity, and banks with insufficient capital to cover debts should be dissolved.
Home equity loans must also be written down.
Policy makers do not want to take this road, this is understandable.
The sanctity of contracts.
The government is worried about losing credibility in the financial market.
If the creditors are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, a write-down will only harm other countries.
These concerns are not unreasonable, but they should not lead to an unreasonable conclusion.
The only way out is internal devaluation or external devaluation.
The leaders of the European countries have to choose between the two.
They have ruled out the option of external devaluation.
But internal devaluation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this point is both unreasonable and illogical.
The operation of debt restructuring is simple and clear.
The government can issue a batch of debt securities, with their face value discounted at a certain ratio from the existing debt face value.
Debt holders can choose, either to stick to exchanging their bonds at face value, but with a later maturity date and lower interest rates; or to accept discounted bonds with a lower face value than their existing bonds, but with an earlier maturity date and higher interest rates.
This is not some cutting-edge technology. Some people have done this before.
But to do it successfully, there are three preconditions.
First, there must be a guarantee to the bond holders that the new bonds are secure.
Someone has to come out to guarantee these bonds.
20th century 80s, when implementing the Brady Plan for Latin American debt restructuring, the role of "guarantor big brother" was played by the US Department of the Treasury.
Nowadays, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
The second is that countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, a country's restructuring will raise expectations for other countries, causing a cascading effect.
Lastly, banks that incur losses due to debt restructuring must have their balance sheets consolidated.
These banks need to undergo a real stress test, not the kind of report they put out earlier this year.
If debt restructuring implies a capital shortfall, then a comprehensive debt-to-equity conversion should be conducted on the relevant banks.
If this is still not enough, then the government must step in to inject capital into the relevant banks.
This also requires unified action from all countries.
Once the banks' balance sheets are consolidated, it may be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debt without shaking the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge right now.
Everything requires decisive leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that the country's banks have a large risk exposure in the eurozone's peripheral countries, and the situation is critical.
They must convince the backroom bosses and voters that using public funds to provide guarantees for debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation; since Germany is urging other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should bear the responsibility of providing guarantees.
In short, European leaders, especially German leaders, must describe the consequences more seriously – if not, they will face a great disaster.
Because the fact is just like that.
